Beginning of this October I had requested about an improvement to reduce the file size of the generated medium 1600px images. You have elegantly solved that in release 0.22.9 by assigning the same quality setting as the original image to the generated one. Many thanks for that, but...

Somehow this is not working for me. At my provider's server ImageMagick is available (Koken is set up for that) and when manually performing "identify -format '%Q' " I do get an according quality value returned (90 in my case). However, when uploading images, the 1600px versions still get a large file size: quality still gets assigned the default of 100.

Doing a little bit of debugging on your code, it seems that the getQuality method always returns 0 for me. Searching further, I find the code of this method somewhat suspicious:

app/koken/Darkroom/DarkroomImageMagick.php:

    public function getQuality()
    {
        ...
        if ($this->isGmagick) {
            $cmd = "identify -format '%Q' ";
        }
        else {
            $cmd = "gm identify -format '%[JPEG-Quality]' ";
        }
      ...
    }

Shouldn't the code in the "if" and "else" branches be exchanged? When I make that change, all is working as it should on my side.

Thanks in advance for taking a look into this.

Best regards,
Peter

A longer while ago there has been a discussion here about the IPTC property that Koken is using to fill out the title of images. Today this is done through the IPTC:ObjectName (= Title) property. Unfortunately there is different software around that is not using this, but the IPTC:Headline property instead. I don't want to start again a discussion here about what is correct or not. I'm using such software and because of that I'm always adapting the app/application/models/content.php file of the Koken installation to support both properties (with priority):

        if (isset($iptc['2#005'])) 
        {
          if (is_array($iptc['2#005']))
          {
            $iptc['2#005'] = $iptc['2#005'][0];
          }
          $this->title = $this->_force_utf($iptc['2#005']);
        } else if (isset($iptc['2#105'])) 
        {
          if (is_array($iptc['2#105']))
          {
            $iptc['2#105'] = $iptc['2#105'][0];
          }
          $this->title = $this->_force_utf($iptc['2#105']);
        }

(I hope the above code remains readable. Adding the part with "2#105".)

I'm asking again if it would be possible to get the above change into the official release of Koken.

Thanks and best regards,
Peter
